SIMPLE: rest
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[For
<ets>arrest</ets>.]</ety> <def>To arrest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>rest</ets>,
<ets>r⟦ae⟧st</ets>, rest; akin to D. <ets>rust</ets>, G.
<ets>rast</ets>. OHG. <ets>rasta</ets>, Dan. & Sw. <ets>rast</ets> rest,
repose, Icel. <ets>r⟦oum⟧st</ets> the distance between two resting
places, a mole, Goth. <ets>rasta</ets> a mile, also to Goth.
<ets>razn</ets> house, Icel. <ets>rann</ets>, and perhaps to G.
<ets>ruhe</ets> rest, repose, AS. <ets>r⟦omac⟧w</ets>, Gr.
<grk>'erwh`</grk>. Cf. <er>Ransack</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A state
of quiet or repose; a cessation from motion or labor; tranquillity;
<as>as, <ex>rest</ex> from mental exertion; <ex>rest</ex> of body or
mind</as>.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sleep give thee all his <qex>rest</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, freedom from everything which wearies or
disturbs; peace; security.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the land had <qex>rest</qex> fourscore years.</q>
<rj><qau>Judges iii. 30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sleep; slumber; hence, poetically, death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How sleep the brave who sink to <qex>rest</qex>,⟦br⟧
By all their country's wishes blest.</q>
<rj><qau>Collins.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That on which anything rests or leans for support;
<as>as, a <ex>rest</ex> in a lathe, for supporting the cutting tool or
steadying the work</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He made narrowed <qex>rests</qex> round about, that the beams
should not be fastened in the walls of the house.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings
vi. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor)</fld> <def>A projection from the right
side of the cuirass, serving to support the lance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their visors closed, their lances in the <qex>rest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A place where one may rest, either temporarily, as
in an inn, or permanently, as, in an abode.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Halfway houses
and travelers' <xex>rests</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J. H.
Newman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In dust our final <qex>rest</qex>, and native home.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye are not as yet come to the <qex>rest</qex> and to the
inheritance which the Lord your God giveth you.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xii.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>A short pause in reading verse; a
caesura.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The striking of a balance at regular intervals in a
running account.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An account is said to be taken with annual
or semiannual <xex>rests</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A set or game at tennis.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Silence in music or in one of its
parts; the name of the character that stands for such silence. They are
named as notes are, <xex>whole</xex>, <xex>half</xex>,
<xex>quarter</xex>,etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Rest house</b></col>, <cd>an empty house for the
accomodation of travelers; a caravansary.</cd> <mark>[India]</mark> --
<mcol><col><b>To set one's rest</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To set up
one's rest</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to have a settled determination; --
from an old game of cards, when one so expressed his intention to stand
or rest upon his hand.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au>
<au>Bacon.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cessation; pause; intermission; stop; stay;
repose; slumber; quiet; ease; quietness; stillness; tranquillity;
peacefulness; peace.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Rest</er>, <er>Repose</er>.
<xex>Rest</xex> is a ceasing from labor or exertion; <xex>repose</xex>
is a mode of resting which gives relief and refreshment after toil and
labor. The words are commonly interchangeable.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw> <pr>(r⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rested</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Resting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>restan</ets>. See
<er>Rest</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cease from
action or motion, especially from action which has caused weariness; to
desist from labor or exertion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God . . . <qex>rested</qex> on the seventh day from all his work
which he had made.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. ii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Six days thou shalt do thy work, and on the seventh day thou shalt
<qex>rest</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxiii. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be free from whatever wearies or disturbs; to be
quiet or still.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There <qex>rest</qex>, if any rest can harbor there.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lie; to repose; to recline; to lan; <as>as, to
<ex>rest</ex> on a couch</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stand firm; to be fixed; to be supported; <as>as,
a column <ex>rests</ex> on its pedestal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To sleep; to slumber; hence, poetically, to be
dead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fancy . . . then retries⟦br⟧
Into her private cell when Nature <qex>rests</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To lean in confidence; to trust; to rely; to repose
without anxiety; <as>as, to <ex>rest</ex> on a man's
promise</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On him I <qex>rested</qex>, after long debate,⟦br⟧
And not without considering, fixed my fate.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To be satisfied; to acquiesce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>rest</qex> in Heaven's determination.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To rest with</b></col>, <cd>to be in the power of; to
depend upon; as, it <xex>rests with</xex> him to decide.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay or place at
rest; to quiet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your piety has paid⟦br⟧
All needful rites, to <qex>rest</qex> my wandering shade.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place, as on a support; to cause to
lean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her weary head upon your bosom <qex>rest</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>reste</ets>, fr.
<ets>rester</ets> to remain, L. <ets>restare</ets> to stay back, remain;
pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>stare</ets> to stand, stay. See
<er>Stand</er>, and cf. <er>Arrest</er>, <er>Restive</er>.]</ety> (With
the definite article.) <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is left, or which
remains after the separation of a part, either in fact or in
contemplation; remainder; residue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Religion gives part of its reward in hand, the present comfort of
having done our duty, and, for the <qex>rest</qex>, it offers us the
best security that Heaven can give.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Those not included in a proposition or description;
the remainder; others.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Plato and the <xex>rest</xex> of the
philosophers.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Armed like the <qex>rest</qex>, the Trojan prince appears.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>A surplus held as a reserved fund
by a bank to equalize its dividends, etc.; in the Bank of England, the
balance of assets above liabilities.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Remainder; overplus; surplus; remnant; residue;
reserve; others.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Rest
<hw>Rest</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>rester</ets>. See
<er>Rest</er> remainder.]</ety> <def>To be left; to remain; to continue
to be.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The affairs of men <qex>rest</qex> still uncertain.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Restagnant</ent>⟦br⟧
